#: Game.Levels.SubgroupDef
msgid "Welcome to **Subgroup Definitions**, where you'll learn what it means\n"
"for a subset of a group to form a group in its own right.\n"
"\n"
"A **subgroup** §0 of a group §1 is a subset that is closed under\n"
"the group operations:\n"
"\n"
"1. The identity §2 belongs to §3\n"
"2. If §4 and §5 belong to §6, then §7 belongs to §8\n"
"3. If §9 belongs to §10, then §11 belongs to §12\n"
"\n"
"Why do we need all three? Consider the positive integers under addition:\n"
"they are closed under addition (the sum of two positive integers is\n"
"positive), but they don't contain the identity §13 and they don't\n"
"contain additive inverses (negatives). So being closed under the\n"
"operation alone is not enough to be a subgroup — you also need the\n"
"identity and inverses.\n"
"\n"
"In Lean, this is captured by the type §14. If §15\n"
"and §16, we write §17 for membership.\n"
"\n"
"The first half of this world teaches you to *use* subgroups — applying\n"
"the membership lemmas §18, §19, and §20. The second\n"
"half teaches you to *build* them — constructing a §21 from\n"
"a carrier set and proving the three closure properties.\n"
"\n"
"By the boss level, you'll prove that the **centralizer** of an element\n"
"§22 — the set §23 of all elements commuting\n"
"with §24 — is a subgroup. This requires all three closure proofs,\n"
"each of which is a real piece of group algebra."
msgstr ""

