#. = 1 * (g * «{a}»⁻¹)             := by rw [one_mul]
#. _ = «{a}»⁻¹ * «{a}» * (g * «{a}»⁻¹)   := by rw [inv_mul_cancel]
#. _ = «{a}»⁻¹ * («{a}» * (g * «{a}»⁻¹)) := by rw [mul_assoc]
#. _ = «{a}»⁻¹ * («{a}» * g * «{a}»⁻¹)   := by rw [← mul_assoc «{a}» g]
#. _ = ...
#. ```
#. §3: `← ha g`
#. §4: `«{a}» * g`
#. §5: `g * «{a}»`
#. §6: `«{a}» * «{a}»⁻¹`
#: Game.Levels.CenterIntro.L04_CenterInv
msgid "Start the §0 block by inserting §1 on the left,\n"
"then re-associate:\n"
"§2\n"
"From here, use §3 to swap §4 to §5, then\n"
"cancel §6."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `(a * b)⁻¹ = b⁻¹ * a⁻¹`
#. §1: `(a * b * c)⁻¹ = c⁻¹ * b⁻¹ * a⁻¹`
#. §2: `group`
#: Game.Levels.GroupBasicsPset.L07_Boss
msgid "The shoes-and-socks lemma says §0. What happens\n"
"with three factors?\n"
"\n"
"Prove that §1.\n"
"\n"
"The §2 tactic is disabled. Work it out by hand."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `H`
#. §1: `H`
#. §2: `g⁻¹ ∈ H`
#. §3: `g ∈ H`
#. §4: `apply Subgroup.mk_carrier`
#. §5: `mul_inv_rev`
#. §6: `mul_mem`
#. §7: `mul_mem hy hx`
#. §8: `mul_mem hx hy`
#. §9: `(x * y)⁻¹ = y⁻¹ * x⁻¹`
#: Game.Levels.SubgroupPset.L05_InverseCarrier
msgid "This subgroup is actually equal to §0 — since §1 is closed under\n"
"inverses, §2 if and only if §3. The point was the\n"
"*proof exercise*: the same §4 pattern works\n"
"regardless of the carrier's surface form.\n"
"\n"
"Notice how §5 (shoes-and-socks from the Group Basics world)\n"
"appeared naturally in §6 — proof moves transfer across worlds.\n"
"Also notice the order swap: §7 instead of §8,\n"
"because §9 reverses the factors."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `map_mul`
#. §1: `map_inv`
#: Game.Levels.HomDef.L08_Boss
msgid "Disabled — decompose using §0 and §1 separately."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `apply mul_left_cancel (a := a)`
#. §1: `a * b = a * 1`
#. §2: `rw [h, mul_one]`
#: Game.Levels.GroupBasicsPset.L02_MulImpliesOne
#: Game.Levels.GroupBasicsPset.L03_RightMulImpliesOne
msgid "Use §0 to reduce\n"
"the goal to §1. Then §2 closes it."
msgstr ""

#: Game.Levels.SubgroupBasics.L01_SubgroupLE
msgid "Subgroup Containment"
msgstr ""

#. §0: `group`
#. §1: `a * (b * a)⁻¹`
#. §2: `group`
#: Game.Levels.GroupBasicsPset.L01_GroupTacticRevisited
msgid "Welcome to the **Group Basics Problem Set** — your first practice world.\n"
"\n"
"In Group Basics, you proved everything by hand with §0 disabled.\n"
"Now it's back. This first problem is a warm-up to remind you of its\n"
"power.\n"
"\n"
"Simplify §1. Try the §2 tactic."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `1`
#. §1: `show (1 : G) = 1`
#. §2: `rfl`
#: Game.Levels.SubgroupDef.L07_BuildingTrivial
msgid "**one_mem**: Show §0 is in the carrier.\n"
"\n"
"§1 to unfold, then §2."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `≤`
#. §1: `H ≤ H`
#. §2: `intro x hx; exact hx`
#. §3: `≤`
#. §4: `hKL (hHK hx)`
#. §5: `x ∈ H`
#. §6: `x ∈ K`
#. §7: `H ≤ K`
#. §8: `x ∈ L`
#. §9: `K ≤ L`
#. §10: `≤`
#. §11: `∀ x, x ∈ H → x ∈ K`
#: Game.Levels.SubgroupPset.L03_LETransitive
msgid "Transitivity of §0 means the subgroup ordering is a *partial order*\n"
"(reflexive, transitive, antisymmetric). Reflexivity (§1) follows\n"
"immediately from §2. Together with the boss's\n"
"antisymmetry proof, these three properties make §3 a genuine partial\n"
"order on the subgroup lattice.\n"
"\n"
"Notice the proof is pure function composition: §4.\n"
"On paper: *If §5, then §6 (since §7), then §8\n"
"(since §9).*\n"
"\n"
"This is what §10 being defined as §11 buys you:\n"
"containment proofs reduce to applying hypotheses."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `g ≠ 1`
#. §1: `zpowers g`
#. §2: `zpowers g`
#. §3: `⊥`
#. §4: `⊤`
#. §5: `zpowers g = ⊥`
#. §6: `g = 1`
#. §7: `zpowers_eq_bot`
#. §8: `g ≠ 1`
#. §9: `zpowers g = ⊤`
#. §10: `zpowers g = ⊥`
#. §11: `g = 1`
#. §12: `Subgroup.zpowers_eq_bot`
#. §13: `rw [Subgroup.zpowers_eq_bot] at hbot`
#. §14: `hbot : zpowers g = ⊥`
#. §15: `hbot : g = 1`
#: Game.Levels.CyclicGroups.L08_ZpowersTopOfPrime
msgid "Time to put the pieces together. In a prime-order group, if §0,\n"
"then §1 must be the whole group.\n"
"\n"
"The argument:\n"
"- §2 is a subgroup, so by the prime-order dichotomy it's\n"
"  either §3 or §4.\n"
"- If §5, then §6 (by §7). But\n"
"  §8 — contradiction.\n"
"- So §9.\n"
"\n"
"This is exactly the dichotomy-plus-contradiction pattern from the\n"
"last level, but now the contradiction comes from converting\n"
"§10 to §11 using §12.\n"
"\n"
"Use §13 to convert a hypothesis\n"
"§14 into §15."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `center G = ⊤`
#. §1: `⊤`
#. §2: `Subgroup.eq_top_iff'`
#. §3: `H = ⊤ ↔ ∀ x, x ∈ H`
#. §4: `center G = ⊤`
#. §5: `mul_comm`
#: Game.Levels.CenterIntro.L05_CenterEqTop
msgid "In a commutative group, every element commutes with everything.\n"
"So the center should be the entire group — §0.\n"
"\n"
"To show a subgroup equals §1, use the lemma §2:\n"
"\n"
"§3\n"
"\n"
"This reduces §4 to showing every element is in the center,\n"
"which follows from §5."
msgstr ""

#. §0: ```
#. (a * b) * (b⁻¹ * a⁻¹)
#. = a * (b * (b⁻¹ * a⁻¹))    -- mul_assoc
#. = a * ((b * b⁻¹) * a⁻¹)    -- ← mul_assoc b b⁻¹ a⁻¹
#. = a * (1 * a⁻¹)             -- mul_inv_cancel
#. = a * a⁻¹                   -- one_mul
#. = 1                          -- mul_inv_cancel
#. ```
#. §1: `calc`
#. §2: `rw [mul_assoc, ← mul_assoc b b⁻¹ a⁻¹, mul_inv_cancel, one_mul, mul_inv_cancel]`
#: Game.Levels.GroupTutorial.L08_Boss
msgid "Here is the plan, step by step:\n"
"§0\n"
"Try writing this as a §1 block or as\n"
"§2."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `Function.Surjective f`
#. §1: `∀ y, ∃ x, f x = y`
#. §2: `«{hs}» : Function.Surjective f`
#. §3: `y`
