#. §0: `x ∈ ⊥`
#. §1: `x = 1`
#. §2: `Subgroup.mem_bot`
#. §3: `1`
#. §4: `mem_bot`
#. §5: `x = 1`
#. §6: `one_mem`
#. §7: `x ∈ ⊥ ∩ H`
#. §8: `x ∈ ⊥`
#. §9: `x ∈ ⊥`
#. §10: `x = 1`
#. §11: `x ∈ H`
#. §12: `1 ∈ H`
#. §13: `x ∈ ⊥`
#. §14: `x ∈ ⊥ ∩ H`
#: Game.Levels.SubgroupPset.L04_BotInfEqBot
msgid "The forward direction was routine extraction. The backward direction\n"
"was the twist: knowing §0 means §1 (via §2),\n"
"then rewriting with this identity reduces everything to facts about §3.\n"
"\n"
"This **reduce-to-identity** pattern — use §4 to learn §5,\n"
"rewrite, then verify using §6 — will recur whenever you reason\n"
"about the trivial subgroup. You'll see it again when proving that an\n"
"injective homomorphism has trivial kernel.\n"
"\n"
"On paper: *Forward: if §7, then §8. Backward: if\n"
"§9, then §10, so §11 (since §12) and §13\n"
"(given), hence §14.*"
msgstr ""

#. §0: `constructor`
#. §1: `A ∧ B`
#. §2: `constructor`
#. §3: `A`
#. §4: `B`
#: Game.Levels.GroupTutorial.L01_RightIdentity
msgid "The §0 tactic splits a goal that is a conjunction or\n"
"a structure with one constructor.\n"
"\n"
"If the goal is §1, then §2 creates two goals:\n"
"one for §3 and one for §4."
