#: Game.Levels.SubgroupBasics.L05_MemInf
msgid "Given two subgroups §0 and §1 of §2, their **intersection**\n"
"§3 (typed §4 or §5) is the subgroup whose elements\n"
"belong to *both* §6 and §7.\n"
"\n"
"The key lemma is §8:\n"
"\n"
"§9\n"
"\n"
"The right-hand side uses §10 (\"and\"). If §11, then\n"
"§12 and §13 extract the two parts.\n"
"\n"
"Given §14, prove that §15."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `isCyclic_iff_exists_zpowers_eq_top`
#. §1: `IsCyclic G ↔ ∃ g, zpowers g = ⊤`
#. §2: `rw [isCyclic_iff_exists_zpowers_eq_top]`
#. §3: `IsCyclic G`
#: Game.Levels.CyclicGroups.L06_IsCyclic
msgid "§0 says:\n"
"\n"
"§1\n"
"\n"
"A group is cyclic if and only if some element's zpowers subgroup\n"
"equals the whole group.\n"
"\n"
"Use §2 to unfold\n"
"§3 in the goal."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `1`
#. §1: `«{a}»`
#. §2: `«{a}» * 1 = 1 * «{a}»`
#. §3: `show «{a}» * 1 = 1 * «{a}»`
#. §4: `rw`
#: Game.Levels.SubgroupDef.L05_ShowTactic
msgid "The goal says §0 belongs to the set of elements commuting\n"
"with §1. This unfolds to §2.\n"
"\n"
"Use §3 to make this explicit, then close the\n"
"goal with §4."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `f`
#. §1: `f`
#. §2: `y ∈ f.range`
#. §3: `x`
#. §4: `f x = y`
#. §5: `G`
#. §6: `H`
#. §7: `f x = 1`
#. §8: `∃ x, f x = y`
#. §9: `mem_range`
#. §10: `⟨x, proof⟩`
#: Game.Levels.HomBasics.L04_RangeDef
msgid "The range of §0 is the set of elements that §1 actually hits.\n"
"To prove §2, you must produce a **witness**: an element\n"
"§3 with §4.\n"
"\n"
"Contrast the two subgroups:\n"
"\n"
"| | Kernel | Range |\n"
"|--|--------|-------|\n"
"| **Lives in** | §5 (source) | §6 (target) |\n"
"| **Membership** | §7 (property) | §8 (witness) |\n"
"| **Measures** | Information destroyed | Information reached |\n"
"\n"
"Kernel reasoning asks: *does this element map to 1?*\n"
"Image reasoning asks: *can I find a preimage?*\n"
"\n"
"The **image-reasoning move**: unfold §9, produce a witness\n"
"§10."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `«{y}» ∈ Subgroup.center G`
#. §1: `h : ∀ (x : G), x ∈ Subgroup.center G`
#. §2: `h «{y}»`
#: Game.Levels.CenterIntro.L06_TopMeansAbelian
msgid "The goal is now §0. You have\n"
"§1, so §2 closes it."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `H`
#. §1: `K`
#. §2: `G`
#. §3: `H ≤ K`
#. §4: `H`
#. §5: `K`
#. §6: `⊥`
#. §7: `{1}`
#. §8: `⊤`
#. §9: `G`
#. §10: `H ⊓ K`
#. §11: `H`
#. §12: `K`
#. §13: `H`
#. §14: `⊥ ≤ H ≤ ⊤`
#. §15: `obtain`
#. §16: `∧`
#. §17: `ext`
#. §18: `∧`
#: Game.Levels.SubgroupBasics
msgid "Welcome to **Subgroup Basics**, where you'll explore how subgroups\n"
"relate to each other.\n"
"\n"
"In the previous world, you learned to *build* individual subgroups by\n"
"verifying three closure properties. Now the question is: given two\n"
"subgroups §0 and §1 of the same group §2, what structure do they\n"
"form?\n"
"\n"
"The answer is a **lattice** — a partially ordered set with meets and\n"
"joins. The key operations are:\n"
"\n"
"- **Containment**: §3 means every element of §4 is also in §5\n"
"- **Bottom**: §6 is the trivial subgroup §7 — the smallest subgroup\n"
"- **Top**: §8 is the whole group §9 — the largest subgroup\n"
"- **Meet (intersection)**: §10 is the largest subgroup contained\n"
"  in both §11 and §12\n"
"\n"
"For any subgroup §13, we always have §14.\n"
"\n"
"You'll also learn two new tactics: §15 for breaking apart\n"
"conjunction hypotheses (§16), and §17 for proving two subgroups\n"
"are equal by checking element-wise membership.\n"
"\n"
"By the boss level, you'll build an intersection subgroup from scratch\n"
"— proving all three closure properties using the membership-triple\n"
"technique from the last world, combined with the new ability to\n"
"destructure §18 hypotheses."
msgstr ""

#: Game.Levels.GroupBasicsPset
msgid "Group Basics Problem Set"
msgstr ""

#. §0: `rw [Subgroup.mem_center_iff] at ha hb ⊢`
#. §1: `ha`
#. §2: `hb`
#. §3: `∀ g, ...`
#: Game.Levels.CenterIntro.L03_CenterMul
msgid "First, unfold center membership everywhere:\n"
"§0\n"
"\n"
"This converts §1, §2, and the goal into their §3 forms."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `G`
#. §1: `Group G`
#. §2: `a * b`
#. §3: `b * a`
#. §4: `a * b = b * a`
#. §5: `a`
#. §6: `b`
#. §7: `CommGroup G`
#. §8: `mul_comm`
#. §9: `a b : G`
#. §10: `G`
#. §11: `CommGroup`
#. §12: `a * b = b * a`
#. §13: `a * b = b * a`
#: Game.Levels.CommGroupIntro.L01_MulComm
msgid "Until now, every group §0 in this game has been a general §1.\n"
"The order of multiplication mattered: §2 and §3 could be\n"
"different things.\n"
"\n"
"A **commutative group** (or **abelian group**) is a group where\n"
"the order doesn't matter: §4 for all §5 and §6.\n"
"In Lean, this is captured by the typeclass §7.\n"
"\n"
"The theorem §8 states: for any §9 where §10 is a\n"
"§11, we have §12.\n"
"\n"
"Prove that §13."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `inv_eq_of_mul_eq_one_right`
#. §1: `a * b = 1`
#. §2: `a⁻¹ = b`
#. §3: `b`
#. §4: `a`
#. §5: `b`
#. §6: `a⁻¹`
#: Game.Levels.GroupBasics.L07_InverseUniqueness
msgid "§0 says that if §1, then §2.\n"
"\n"
"The inverse is unique: if §3 is a right inverse of §4, then §5\n"
"must equal §6. This is the main tool for proving that a specific\n"
"expression equals an inverse."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `a * b⁻¹ = 1`
#. §1: `a`
#. §2: `b`
#: Game.Levels.GroupBasicsPset.L06_MulInvEqOneImpliesEq
msgid "If §0, what can you conclude about §1 and §2?\n"
"\n"
"This problem requires combining two tools from Group Basics:\n"
"inverse uniqueness and the injectivity of inversion."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `inv_mul_cancel`
#. §1: `a⁻¹ * a = 1`
#. §2: `mul_inv_cancel`
#. §3: `a * a⁻¹ = 1`
#. §4: `mul_inv_cancel`
#. §5: `a * a⁻¹`
#. §6: `inv_mul_cancel`
#. §7: `a⁻¹ * a`
#: Game.Levels.GroupTutorial.L04_LeftInverse
msgid "The theorem §0 says that §1 — the inverse\n"
"cancels on the **left** too.\n"
"\n"
"Together with §2 (which says §3), you now\n"
"have cancellation in both directions.\n"
"\n"
"The naming convention continues: §4 has the inverse on the\n"
"**right** (§5), while §6 has the inverse on the\n"
"**left** (§7)."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `x`
#. §1: `x⁻¹`
#. §2: `intro x hx`
#: Game.Levels.SubgroupDef.L07_BuildingTrivial
msgid "**inv_mem**: If §0 is in the carrier, then §1 is too.\n"
"\n"
"Start with §2."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `induction n with`
#. §1: ```
#. induction n with
#. | zero => sorry
#. | succ n ih => sorry
#. ```
#. §2: `sorry`
#: Game.Levels.CommGroupIntro.L04_OnePow
msgid "Use §0 to split into base case and\n"
"induction step. The syntax is:\n"
"§1\n"
"Replace each §2 with the actual proof."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `mul_right_cancel`
#. §1: `a * b = c * b`
#. §2: `a = c`
#. §3: `mul_left_cancel`
#: Game.Levels.GroupBasics.L06_RightCancel
msgid "§0 says that if §1, then §2.\n"
"\n"
"This is the **right cancellation law**: you can cancel a common right\n"
"factor in a group. Mirror of §3."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `G`
#. §1: `H ⊆ G`
#. §2: `Subgroup G`
#. §3: `H : Subgroup G`
#. §4: `x : G`
#. §5: `x ∈ H`
#. §6: `x`
#. §7: `H`
#. §8: `∈`
#. §9: `1`
#. §10: `one_mem`
#. §11: `one_mem H : 1 ∈ H`
#. §12: `1`
#. §13: `H`
#: Game.Levels.SubgroupDef.L01_SubgroupMembership
msgid "A **subgroup** of a group §0 is a subset §1 that is itself a\n"
"group under the same operation. In Lean, this is captured by the type\n"
"§2.\n"
"\n"
"If §3 and §4, we write §5 to say that §6\n"
"belongs to the subgroup §7. This uses the same §8 notation you know\n"
"from sets.\n"
"\n"
"Every subgroup contains the identity element §9. This is the theorem\n"
"§10:\n"
"\n"
"§11\n"
"\n"
"Prove that §12 belongs to §13."
msgstr ""

#: Game.Levels.CenterIntro
msgid "The Center"
msgstr ""

